1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,558
In some sense the goal of mathematics is

2
00:00:02,658 --> 00:00:05,150
to add enough axioms such that there is

3
00:00:05,266 --> 00:00:08,876
exactly one structure which satisfies them.

4
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:12,267
In this case, the theory of Sigma is a perfect description of

5
00:00:12,367 --> 00:00:16,629
the structure, it contains everything we could possibly say about the structure

6
00:00:16,729 --> 00:00:19,610
in first order logic in the language of the structure.

7
00:00:19,733 --> 00:00:22,395
If a theory has a finite model, then there is

8
00:00:22,495 --> 00:00:26,262
a single sentence phi which fully characterizes the theory, and

9
00:00:26,362 --> 00:00:29,638
therefore there is exactly one model up to isomorphism.

10
00:00:29,733 --> 00:00:32,429
However, in the third video, we will see why

11
00:00:32,529 --> 00:00:35,798
this is impossible for a theory with infinite models.

12
00:00:35,866 --> 00:00:39,881
But we can still achieve something weaker, namely that all

13
00:00:39,981 --> 00:00:43,498
models of our set Sigma satisfy the same sentences.

14
00:00:43,600 --> 00:00:46,763
You may ask how we can know that two models M and N are

15
00:00:46,863 --> 00:00:51,570
actually different if they satisfy the same sentences. Again, we will see this in

16
00:00:51,670 --> 00:00:55,309
the third video, but for now just know that this has to do with

17
00:00:55,409 --> 00:00:59,878
the inability of First Order Logic to deal with the complexities of infinity.

18
00:00:59,933 --> 00:01:03,478
However, if we have such a set Sigma, then we cannot

19
00:01:03,578 --> 00:01:08,244
differentiate any of its models using a single first order sentence.

20
00:01:08,333 --> 00:01:12,429
So, given any sentence alpha we can write, either every

21
00:01:12,529 --> 00:01:16,853
model satisfies it, or every model satisfies its negation.

22
00:01:16,933 --> 00:01:20,594
In this case we say that the theory is complete.

23
00:01:20,666 --> 00:01:25,974
Syntactically, completeness means that the theory is maximally consistent, in

24
00:01:26,074 --> 00:01:29,837
the sense that for every formula alpha, either alpha is

25
00:01:29,937 --> 00:01:32,295
in Sigma, or not alpha is in Sigma.

26
00:01:33,333 --> 00:01:38,562
Thus, it decides everything that it possibly can.

27
00:01:38,600 --> 00:01:42,855
If we added even a single new formula alpha to a complete theory,

28
00:01:42,955 --> 00:01:47,747
it would then become inconsistent, and it would therefore have no models.

